WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.320
Welcome, my name is Kate Hertweck, I'm the bioinformatics training manager at Fred Hutchinson

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:15.720
Cancer Research Center in Seattle, Washington.

00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:21.740
My career focus is helping scientists learn the coding and data skills they need to apply

00:00:21.740 --> 00:00:26.840
cutting edge computational methods and accelerate the rate of science.

00:00:26.840 --> 00:00:32.040
I'm excited to tell you about one of the best parts of my job, helping researchers

00:00:32.040 --> 00:00:37.680
unlock the mindset and tools that help them make the most of their data and get more work

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:40.279
done in less time.

00:00:40.279 --> 00:00:45.439
Here's how the general process of teaching someone R usually happens.

00:00:45.439 --> 00:00:51.119
I work for a biomedical research center with a huge breadth of research topics, but everyone

00:00:51.119 --> 00:00:53.740
wants to make figures for publication.

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:58.900
My community loves R, especially Tidyverse, because it makes sense to them to be able

00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:01.220
to achieve those goals.

00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:06.980
In my introductory R class, I start by teaching some general skills in data manipulation and

00:01:06.980 --> 00:01:08.820
filtering.

00:01:08.820 --> 00:01:14.699
My participants learn to create elegant, effective data visualizations that help them explore

00:01:14.699 --> 00:01:16.860
their data.

00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:22.199
After a few hours bent over their keyboards, I can see the slowly dawning realization in

00:01:22.199 --> 00:01:23.480
their eyes.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:28.639
With the power unlocked by coding, I will surely obtain a statistically significant

00:01:28.639 --> 00:01:34.360
result supporting my insightful hypothesis, yielding fame and glory, but more importantly,

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:39.879
a paper in Nature or Science, as well as future grant funding.

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:44.599
In case you're not a scientist and this doesn't resonate with you, let's think about it from

00:01:44.599 --> 00:01:49.839
a layperson's, well, lay dog's perspective.

00:01:49.839 --> 00:01:54.720
For scientists, unlocking the power of coding is like when we're dogs getting a one-way

00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:59.800
ticket to the dog park, complete with all of our favorite toys and lots of interesting

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:02.760
things to sniff.

00:02:02.760 --> 00:02:10.679
That moment when the dog realizes the dog park is near is like that moment when an important

00:02:10.679 --> 00:02:17.639
concept about data or computational work clicks for someone learning R, and they see a world

00:02:17.639 --> 00:02:21.000
of opportunity open up for them.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:28.639
Unfortunately, all too often, when the time comes to apply their skills to their own data,

00:02:28.639 --> 00:02:33.039
they're confronted with a console that looks more like this.

00:02:33.039 --> 00:02:40.160
These red error messages are sometimes scary, often confusing, and always frustrating.

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:46.119
The prevalent feeling they experience is disappointment, tinged with a touch of, how am I supposed

00:02:46.119 --> 00:02:52.160
to achieve fame and glory when I can't even get R to acknowledge my data exists?

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:59.360
That crushing defeat in the face of such promise is also something a dog can relate to.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:03.600
It's the equivalent of jumping in the car, thinking we're heading to the dog park.

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:09.639
We can almost feel the breeze, taste the rubber ball in our mouth, and smell the grass, instead

00:03:09.639 --> 00:03:12.279
ending up at the vet.

00:03:12.279 --> 00:03:16.800
This is exactly the opposite of what we wanted.

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:23.160
It's disappointing and demoralizing, so much so that we don't want to get in the car again,

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:29.240
even if we might end up at the dog park eventually someday.

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:37.440
So how do we jump over this barrier, restoring a belief that we can achieve those lofty goals?

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:42.839
When I accepted my current position to develop and implement a training program in reproducible

00:03:42.839 --> 00:03:48.440
computational methods two and a half years ago, I thought the most important part of

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:52.119
my job would be time spent in a classroom.

00:03:52.119 --> 00:03:57.119
I had spent the previous four years teaching computational skills to students at the university

00:03:57.119 --> 00:04:03.199
level, and after an entire career in academia, I thought that the highest impact I could

00:04:03.199 --> 00:04:10.279
have at a research center would involve teaching formally structured short courses.

00:04:10.279 --> 00:04:15.039
During my career, I've had the privilege of personally teaching hundreds of people to

00:04:15.039 --> 00:04:21.160
code in R. Especially in my last few years focusing on adult learners outside of formal

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:26.679
university courses, I've learned a lot about what it takes to help people succeed in learning

00:04:26.679 --> 00:04:33.359
R, and that success is not solely reliant on formal short courses.

00:04:33.359 --> 00:04:40.239
Now I define success as whether people continue to work with R after leaving my classroom,

00:04:40.239 --> 00:04:45.559
or at least if they gain some general literacy in data and computing skills so they can work

00:04:45.559 --> 00:04:49.600
more effectively with computational staff.

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:54.799
Given the breadth of research topics members of my community pursue, I am faced with the

00:04:54.799 --> 00:05:00.320
monumental task of helping people apply R skills to many different types of data and

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:02.679
research questions.

00:05:02.679 --> 00:05:08.559
The question I then continually ask myself as I prepare to deliver training materials

00:05:08.559 --> 00:05:15.519
is this, what prevents people from using these tools after they've learned them?

00:05:15.519 --> 00:05:19.720
Let's take a quick tour of the process of gaining expertise and think about what this

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:23.000
looks like with coding.

00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:28.079
Regardless of the prior education someone possesses in a different field, I consider

00:05:28.079 --> 00:05:33.440
a person who has no prior experience learning to code in R a novice.

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:38.440
In my community, that means they probably don't have any experience coding in a different

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:43.480
language and probably also don't know much about how to structure and store their data

00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:45.079
effectively.

00:05:45.079 --> 00:05:50.839
I integrate general concepts in coding and data management into my intro R course and

00:05:50.839 --> 00:05:55.600
focus on directly applicable skills like those I showed in code earlier.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:06:00.320
By the time someone has completed my introductory R class, I like to think that they're no

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:06.519
longer a novice, since they have now transitioned to competent practitioner.

00:06:06.519 --> 00:06:12.920
I define a competent practitioner as someone who applies R code to their own research problems.

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:17.940
A practitioner probably doesn't know if the way that they code represents the most elegant

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:23.179
or efficient solution to a problem, but they get the job done.

00:06:23.179 --> 00:06:28.420
I consider expert-level coders to be people who are writing code that make it easy for

00:06:28.420 --> 00:06:30.820
other people to use it.

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:37.000
They encapsulate their projects in fully documented R packages and try to apply best practices

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:42.820
in coding to make it robust and reproducible.

00:06:42.820 --> 00:06:48.339
To be clear, I'm less concerned about formally categorizing people into these groups.

00:06:48.339 --> 00:06:52.859
I think more about how to help people follow the arrows to the right.

00:06:52.859 --> 00:06:59.660
In practice, most people I encounter are practitioners of some type, most often interested in getting

00:06:59.660 --> 00:07:01.700
the immediate job done.

00:07:01.700 --> 00:07:06.859
Regardless, this model is a really useful way to think about a few key questions.

00:07:06.859 --> 00:07:09.000
What do people need to learn?

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:13.079
And how are they most likely to learn these things?

00:07:13.079 --> 00:07:17.040
We're going to investigate these questions by visiting a few colleagues of mine who generally

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:21.660
represent each of these categories.

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:23.399
Please meet Ash.

00:07:23.399 --> 00:07:29.320
Ash is trained in software engineering and currently works in data management and software

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:35.600
development in a research lab, writing software for scientists to use for research purposes.

00:07:35.799 --> 00:07:39.119
Ash is writing a package named Borker.

00:07:39.119 --> 00:07:44.040
Borker creates maps indicating density of dogs being walked in certain areas of a city

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:45.799
at certain times.

00:07:45.799 --> 00:07:51.440
Ash hopes that Borker will be used for both public dog health tracking, as well as integration

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:55.279
with the dog social media network, Snoot Bork.

00:07:55.279 --> 00:08:00.559
However, Ash hasn't worked much with maps lately, and Ash needs to know the best approaches

00:08:00.559 --> 00:08:03.579
in R to achieve their goals.

00:08:03.579 --> 00:08:09.540
What Ash does is go and asks on Twitter and some local Slack communities for their recommendations.

00:08:09.540 --> 00:08:15.179
They are able to narrow down the options available based on what they and their friends understand

00:08:15.179 --> 00:08:18.220
about the project requirements.

00:08:18.220 --> 00:08:23.179
Ash goes ahead and references the relevant documentation for each option, and given their

00:08:23.179 --> 00:08:28.019
breadth of knowledge, Ash can quickly identify the relevant functions and how to connect

00:08:28.059 --> 00:08:34.219
them together to implement mapping in the context of Borker.

00:08:34.219 --> 00:08:37.219
One of Ash's colleagues is named Avery.

00:08:37.219 --> 00:08:41.940
Avery is a graduate student with some formal coursework in data science, but is still learning

00:08:41.940 --> 00:08:46.419
the best methods for optimizing workflows in R.

00:08:46.419 --> 00:08:51.780
Avery is developing documentation for a group of summer interns and wants to streamline

00:08:51.780 --> 00:08:55.580
the process of creating projects with them.

00:08:55.619 --> 00:09:00.539
Avery goes and asks Ash, who recommends the package, use this.

00:09:00.539 --> 00:09:05.179
Avery is really excited, goes and takes a look at the main documentation page, and is

00:09:05.179 --> 00:09:07.099
really intimidated.

00:09:07.099 --> 00:09:11.140
They haven't worked with a package like this before, and they also haven't worked much

00:09:11.140 --> 00:09:16.840
with Git or GitHub, which is one of the really awesome features involved in use this.

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:22.580
They especially aren't comfortable in their ability to use this package and help other

00:09:22.580 --> 00:09:25.900
people use the tool as well.

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:29.140
So Avery comes to my office hours and asks for help.

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:37.460
I point them towards a project from our colleagues' lab that actually applies use this.

00:09:37.460 --> 00:09:44.179
This particular project is a template that includes working with GitHub, starting an

00:09:44.179 --> 00:09:51.859
analysis, and explaining why their particular approach works for data analysis projects.

00:09:51.859 --> 00:09:57.380
The explanation Avery needed didn't just include the code to run, but an example of

00:09:57.380 --> 00:10:02.299
how all the pieces would fit together in a final project.

00:10:02.299 --> 00:10:06.619
Avery is really excited about this breakthrough and uses the package to support their summer

00:10:06.619 --> 00:10:09.179
intern, Quinn.

00:10:09.179 --> 00:10:14.739
Quinn is an undergraduate in biology who has recently started learning computational methods.

00:10:14.739 --> 00:10:19.580
Quinn thought my intro R class was quite intuitive and is eager to apply their skills to their

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:21.799
summer project.

00:10:21.799 --> 00:10:26.239
However, they ended up encountering the same problem I showed at the beginning of this

00:10:26.239 --> 00:10:31.559
talk, errors associated with read underscore CSV.

00:10:31.559 --> 00:10:39.039
Now Quinn knows how to use the help function to share information about it.

00:10:39.039 --> 00:10:44.239
And then they encounter what is, in my opinion, one of the great contradictions of computing.

00:10:44.239 --> 00:10:50.119
The simpler a function seems, the more complicated the help documentation appears, especially

00:10:50.119 --> 00:10:52.760
to someone new to coding.

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:57.599
Quinn's reaction is similar to the general response I get from a novice learner's first

00:10:57.599 --> 00:11:04.320
glance at this help documentation, a bit of abject horror, thinking, what have I done?

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:10.000
However, Quinn goes and talks to Avery, who helps them think about the basics of R coding,

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:14.940
the structure of their data, and how their project is organized, ultimately helping them

00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:21.580
understand how to piece together that information to import their data.

00:11:21.580 --> 00:11:27.380
These of course are the problems with which we all grapple on a nearly daily basis.

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:32.739
How do we prioritize how to exert our energy, especially when we have different goals with

00:11:32.739 --> 00:11:37.659
competing interests, and it's not clear whether or not the effort we're exerting is going

00:11:37.659 --> 00:11:40.880
to make a huge difference in the long run?

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:45.400
These questions include things like, do I write a vignette or add a new feature to the

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:47.320
package I'm developing?

00:11:47.320 --> 00:11:52.000
Do I keep trying to get this function to work for my analysis, or do I give up and try something

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:53.200
else?

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:58.780
How do I even find the help I need to address this key issue?

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:04.320
As it turns out, even small differences in how support materials are developed can make

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:09.659
the difference between someone struggling and wrestling with implementing a new approach

00:12:09.700 --> 00:12:13.419
or being able to take the ball and run with it.

00:12:13.419 --> 00:12:21.539
This is because, in my experience, learning specific technical skills is easy.

00:12:21.539 --> 00:12:27.859
However, once you've learned how a technical skill generally operates, being able to apply

00:12:27.859 --> 00:12:32.580
that to your own problem is much more difficult.

00:12:32.580 --> 00:12:38.739
The usefulness of training and documentation depends on both what information is provided

00:12:38.739 --> 00:12:42.340
and how it's delivered.

00:12:42.340 --> 00:12:46.979
Now that we have an idea of the problem we face, how do we actually meet these needs?

00:12:46.979 --> 00:12:52.940
So far, I've made some generally vague references to training materials and documentation.

00:12:52.940 --> 00:12:56.260
I think it's worth highlighting what some of these options include.

00:12:56.260 --> 00:13:01.099
And if you'd like more information on detailed descriptions of types of materials, head over

00:13:01.099 --> 00:13:06.380
to the resources I've included in our studio's collection of conference materials.

00:13:06.380 --> 00:13:08.619
First, manuals.

00:13:08.619 --> 00:13:14.140
We have a baseline expectation in the R community that a standardized user manual documenting

00:13:14.140 --> 00:13:17.640
features of a package is included.

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:22.140
This particular documentation provides basic information like how does a function work

00:13:22.140 --> 00:13:25.619
and what options are available for working with the function.

00:13:25.619 --> 00:13:32.419
In my experience, manuals are most useful for expert users or people who have some familiarity

00:13:32.419 --> 00:13:36.900
with how the particular type of function can work.

00:13:36.900 --> 00:13:40.099
Another type of material is vignettes.

00:13:40.099 --> 00:13:45.539
Vignettes answer questions like how do functions work together to answer general questions.

00:13:45.539 --> 00:13:50.700
These tend to be more like demos or tutorials for implementing code, which ends up making

00:13:50.700 --> 00:13:55.380
them much more accessible for a broad variety of users.

00:13:55.380 --> 00:14:00.400
A third type of support material are example projects or code.

00:14:00.400 --> 00:14:07.080
These demonstrate what an applicable, authentic project incorporating a tool looks like.

00:14:07.080 --> 00:14:11.000
And these end up being very crucial, especially for practitioners.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:17.719
Fourth, formally structured, in-depth short courses are generally in highest demand for

00:14:17.719 --> 00:14:21.400
novices and often something that most people are familiar with.

00:14:21.400 --> 00:14:25.000
They would like someone to tell them what the answers are.

00:14:25.599 --> 00:14:31.679
Now, each of these different approaches requires a different amount of effort to both find,

00:14:31.679 --> 00:14:36.440
if you're wanting to learn from it, or develop, if you are creating it.

00:14:36.440 --> 00:14:39.599
And sometimes these resources do blend together.

00:14:39.599 --> 00:14:44.960
They're also generally supplemented by conversations with colleagues, which I've found is one of

00:14:44.960 --> 00:14:49.760
the most valuable ways to fill in knowledge gaps.

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:54.960
Now that we've considered how types of support vary based on levels of expertise, let's return

00:14:54.960 --> 00:14:56.239
to Ash.

00:14:56.239 --> 00:15:01.479
Ash is excited that their package is nearing completion, so they share the manual with

00:15:01.479 --> 00:15:03.479
Avery and Quinn.

00:15:03.479 --> 00:15:08.400
Avery has trouble understanding how some of the Borker functions work, but learns a lot

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:11.359
in the process of trying to figure it out.

00:15:11.359 --> 00:15:20.159
Quinn doesn't understand any of it, including that Ash actually wrote the package, and then

00:15:20.159 --> 00:15:23.520
Quinn tries to Google it to find more information.

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:28.080
They come across search results for a Chinese death metal band by the same name, and Ash

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:32.919
ultimately regrets not Googling the name before deciding on it for their package.

00:15:32.919 --> 00:15:37.760
At this point, Ash has a choice, continue the package development to integrate with

00:15:37.760 --> 00:15:42.840
Snoot Bork, or make it clearer what the package is doing right now.

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:48.260
Ash decides to ask Avery to collaborate on explaining how functions fit together more

00:15:48.260 --> 00:15:49.760
clearly in a vignette.

00:15:50.479 --> 00:15:56.400
They are supported by another of Ash's colleagues, who have developed some code using Borker,

00:15:56.400 --> 00:16:00.320
which Ash is happy to reference in the documentation for the package.

00:16:00.320 --> 00:16:04.520
Quinn keeps attending meetings and learns a lot about the process of code collaboration,

00:16:04.520 --> 00:16:08.320
and eventually even clarifies a few instructions in the manual.

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:14.520
This story from my colleagues is one example of the process of developing documentation.

00:16:14.520 --> 00:16:17.599
What does it mean in broader practice, though?

00:16:17.640 --> 00:16:22.799
There are countless online classes, tutorials, demos, and other resources that can help you

00:16:22.799 --> 00:16:29.119
learn R. These are approaches that walk us through the process of some coding tasks,

00:16:29.119 --> 00:16:32.239
essentially leading you by a leash.

00:16:32.239 --> 00:16:37.200
Given that availability, why do people keep coming into my classroom?

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:41.799
What I've learned really makes or breaks progression to higher levels of expertise

00:16:41.919 --> 00:16:47.960
is access to information that helps fill in the biggest gaps in our knowledge.

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:53.520
My job as a trainer is to provide guidance that fills in those gaps, which allows learners

00:16:53.520 --> 00:17:00.520
to keep moving in the same direction, but without a leash, so that they have guidance,

00:17:00.520 --> 00:17:03.520
but more importantly, autonomy.

00:17:03.520 --> 00:17:10.540
So while I'm developing support materials, I consider identifying what knowledge is assumed

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:16.699
in the materials I'm developing, as well as collecting curated examples of code that

00:17:16.699 --> 00:17:20.260
apply methods commonly desired in my community.

00:17:20.260 --> 00:17:26.300
In fact, one of the most effective things we can do is share high-quality training materials

00:17:26.300 --> 00:17:31.180
with the people for whom they are most suited.

00:17:31.180 --> 00:17:36.420
The ecosystem of tools available in the R community really reflects the interests of

00:17:36.420 --> 00:17:39.339
the people comprising that community.

00:17:39.339 --> 00:17:44.859
With so many tools to maintain and develop, is it worth developing and maintaining support

00:17:44.859 --> 00:17:46.819
materials, too?

00:17:46.819 --> 00:17:52.699
Well, we share our code so other people can benefit from our hard work, and to increase

00:17:52.699 --> 00:17:55.300
the impact of our efforts.

00:17:55.300 --> 00:18:00.579
If sharing our code results in a multiplier effect for our effort, then making it easier

00:18:00.579 --> 00:18:05.020
for people to use the code multiplies it yet again.

00:18:05.020 --> 00:18:10.699
At a time when disparities in the world feel more stark than ever, access to information

00:18:10.699 --> 00:18:16.439
makes a huge difference in promoting equity for developing these skills.

00:18:16.439 --> 00:18:21.859
These values are why we support open science projects, and that means considering how even

00:18:21.859 --> 00:18:26.859
our small actions can continue to uphold these values.

00:18:26.859 --> 00:18:31.339
In many cases, we don't even have to create these materials ourselves.

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:39.459
Knowing what resources exist and helping raise their visibility can have a huge impact, too.

00:18:39.459 --> 00:18:43.900
Regardless of what level of expertise you think best describes you, please consider

00:18:43.900 --> 00:18:45.979
the following.

00:18:45.979 --> 00:18:51.420
For those of us beginning to code in R, it's likely we'll encounter a piece of documentation

00:18:51.420 --> 00:18:53.780
we don't understand.

00:18:53.780 --> 00:18:56.859
That's okay, and it's not our fault.

00:18:56.859 --> 00:19:01.099
That information probably isn't written to be accessible for people with our type

00:19:01.099 --> 00:19:02.900
of expertise.

00:19:02.900 --> 00:19:07.420
There's almost certainly a better resource out there, or materials that can help us bridge

00:19:07.420 --> 00:19:09.780
that gap.

00:19:09.780 --> 00:19:15.660
For those of us who are practitioners, worrying that, even if our code works, it just isn't

00:19:15.660 --> 00:19:18.619
good enough, it's okay.

00:19:18.619 --> 00:19:21.300
Every expert coder has been where we are now.

00:19:21.300 --> 00:19:25.979
There's also no requirement that we keep learning more advanced skills, but the community

00:19:25.979 --> 00:19:31.140
is here to help us, and it'll probably be very satisfying to learn.

00:19:31.140 --> 00:19:37.219
Finally, those of us who are experts developing R packages, unsure how to make the information

00:19:37.219 --> 00:19:41.060
accessible to a broad audience, it's okay.

00:19:41.060 --> 00:19:46.819
This is a great opportunity for us to collaborate with someone with a different type of expertise.

00:19:46.819 --> 00:19:52.459
These relationships can help us share our tools more broadly while supporting other

00:19:52.459 --> 00:19:57.260
community members in advancing their own skills.

00:19:57.260 --> 00:20:01.819
For all of us struggling to communicate with people who possess different knowledge and

00:20:01.819 --> 00:20:06.739
skills, remember this is something everyone confronts.

00:20:06.739 --> 00:20:13.020
Given that we're all continually learning things, and yes, also forgetting things periodically,

00:20:13.020 --> 00:20:18.060
our own knowledge and that of those around us is constantly changing too, making for

00:20:18.060 --> 00:20:20.979
a sometimes rapidly moving target.

00:20:20.979 --> 00:20:25.339
One of the best things we can do for each other is understand that we can't expect

00:20:25.339 --> 00:20:31.319
a resource to be one size fits all, and that helping someone else learn is a way of supporting

00:20:31.319 --> 00:20:36.180
the entire community, as well as yourself in the future.

00:20:36.180 --> 00:20:40.819
I learned about the basic framework of levels of expertise from the Carpentries.

00:20:40.819 --> 00:20:45.900
This nonprofit group teaches reproducible data and computing skills, including R, to

00:20:45.979 --> 00:20:51.619
communities worldwide and have a number of resources related to training diverse audiences

00:20:51.619 --> 00:20:54.300
and technical skills.

00:20:54.300 --> 00:20:58.739
My current work at Fred Hutch builds on methods and materials from the Carpentries.

00:20:58.739 --> 00:21:04.739
I've adapted their workshop content to directly apply to the research community I serve.

00:21:04.739 --> 00:21:11.099
We otherwise apply the concepts I've discussed here to training and community development.

00:21:11.099 --> 00:21:16.339
I'm also proud to be advising MetaDocencia, a group focused on a different type of targeted

00:21:16.339 --> 00:21:22.300
community development, supporting educational practices for Spanish-speaking communities,

00:21:22.300 --> 00:21:26.099
and this includes teaching technical skills.

00:21:26.099 --> 00:21:31.180
Each of these groups facilitate training for diverse audiences and demonstrate how even

00:21:31.180 --> 00:21:37.979
small changes can mean a lot for individual learners in the R community.

00:21:37.979 --> 00:21:41.459
If you'd like more information about the ideas I've mentioned here, check out the

00:21:41.459 --> 00:21:45.780
resources I've included in RStudio's collection of conference materials.

00:21:45.780 --> 00:21:49.979
If you'd like to talk about computational training and customizing R resources, follow

00:21:49.979 --> 00:21:51.339
me on Twitter.

00:21:51.339 --> 00:21:55.540
I can also recommend my Twitter account if you'd like to see pictures of my favorite

00:21:55.540 --> 00:21:57.619
coworker, Loki.

00:21:57.619 --> 00:22:03.380
He wouldn't consider himself to be even a novice R coder, but he does listen very intently

00:22:03.380 --> 00:22:07.660
to all of my thoughts about training and community building.

00:22:07.660 --> 00:22:13.500
Thanks for watching, and for helping support a bigger, more inclusive global R community.

